{"type":"message","id":"25741024","parentId":"23bc02e0","timestamp":"2026-04-14T15:01:46.403Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me compare the current sessions state against the heartbeat state from the last report.\n\n**Last Report (14:30 UTC) sessions:**\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d` — running ✅\n- `cron:6f3323ef` — running ✅\n- `cron:e7885813` — running ✅\n- `telegram:group:-5163901258` — running (resumed at ~14:23 UTC)\n- `telegram:group:-5168104492` — done ✅\n- `telegram:direct:6053576134` — done ✅\n\n\n- `main` — done ✅\n- `cron:b653a6c0` (zombie) — running (stale)\n- `cron:ac986a8d` (zombie) — running (stale)\n\n**Current sessions (14:59 UTC):**\nLooking at the session list, I see the cron jobs are still running with updated timestamps — the QLHV cron and the other cron have both been refreshed since the last check.\n\nThe QLHV group is running, the Lead direct message is done, the agent status cron is running, the main cron is done, and I'm seeing a few other agents listed that I need to cross-reference with the full state.\n\nLooking at the complete session list, I count 20 sessions total, but many are stale zombies, failed subagents, or old killed sessions that don't matter. The critical ones that are actually active are the three cron jobs, the QLHV group, and the agent status cron — those five are what I need to track. I'm noticing that most of the older cron and subagent sessions are stale or completed, so I need to update my heartbeat check. The critical active sessions are the three cron jobs and the Telegram group, and compared to the 14:30 UTC baseline, I need to verify which sessions have changed status since then. Now I'm verifying that all the critical sessions remain in the same state—no changes detected. I'll update the heartbeat state with the new timestamps and exit silently, then write out the updated JSON.","thinkingSignature":"0b30160e42f3350ae132cf158055bc04bff4bdad2f69123c7ac2b92d3e5c6153"},{"type":"text",